Have an urgent question that can’t wait? Call me (Mr. Houseknecht) at 869-9636, ext 3101. Calls to that extension get forwarded to my cell phone. For all non-urgent questions, please leave a message for the middle/high school secretaries.

April 24 Updates

Middle School We Stay Home For Each Other video # 1. This is great - please watch!

April 14 Updates

High School Phone Message on April 15:

Our new return date is Monday, May 18. If that changes, I will let you know. 

Most students are engaging in class and turning in assignments, which is great. All students need to realize that they are being held accountable for their learning even though we are not physically in the classroom. The work students do now and have done while we have been out will be counted for a grade and credit for the courses they are taking.

The state has suspended Regents exams for this June. Students in Regents classes can earn Regents credit without taking the test IF they pass the course. 

For the high school, we are sending out comment only report cards for the 3rd quarter. You should have those during the first week of May. There will be no number grades on report cards for the 3rd quarter. The reason for this is that we wanted to make sure both teachers and students had the time to ramp up to this new online format, which is very challenging for any school; teachers, students and parents included. 

You can easily reach me with any questions. All one has to do is to call the school at 869-9636, ext. 3101. If I’m not in the office, it goes to my cell phone. 

Do you need to pick something up or drop something off? I am available in the office from 9 to noon Monday through Thursday. Let me know if those times don’t work for you. Notes are on my “school closing updates” page, which is linked from the HS home page. 

Please remind your child that the building is closed but school is open. These and other updates are on the hs home page at southseneca.org Thank you for your help during this challenging time, and I hope you have a great day. 


Cornell Cooperative Extension Update

The CCE staff has developed a ”COVID-19 Working from Home Toolkit” on our website. It includes:
Local Foods Within Your Reach, which provides info on food pantries, farm stands, school districts, restaurants, and hunting and fishing.
Food Safety, that includes information on utilizing food from your freezer and pantry along with FDA resources.
Working from home, providing resources for those new to working from home including how to set up your space, using various platforms, and ISP info.
Resources for Teachers and Parents, has resources including activities and videos in the areas of classes, resources/curricula, virtual tours, and on-line education and meetings. This is rather extensive and being added to regularly. 
FLX 4-H Learning Launchpad http://senecacountycce.org/covid19-staying-at-home-toolkit/flx-4-h-learning-launchpad This is a repository for daily learning opportunities from Finger Lakes area 4-H educators, offered via Facebook at 10 AM each weekday: https://www.facebook.com/FLX4HLearningLaunchpad/ . April 7 Updates

School restart date: Our current restart date is April 29th. We had to extend it to this date by order of the governor. 

Picking something up?
Mr. Houseknecht will be in the office from 9 to 12 on Mondays to Thursdays. If you need something, or if Mr. H isn’t here, call 869-9636, ext. 3101. That goes to Mr. H’s cell phone after a few rings. 

Stay Engaged! Teachers are making monumental efforts to keep course material available to students. Some students are not engaging. Please contact me (Mr. H) directly if you need help with anything. 

Narrative reports for the Middle School: Instead of 3rd quarter report cards, Middle School teachers will be completing narrative reports, which should be to you by May 1st or so. Once we know what will be happening with the remainder of the school year, we will make the determination on how we determine grades. Stay tuned. 

Reports for the High School: Narrative reports will be sent out for struggling students, which includes students who are not engaging to this point. These reports will go out at approximately the same time as the Middle School narratives. It’s extremely important for students to make their best effort in engaging with the course material and communicating with the teacher. A determination on final grades has yet to be determined. This will depend on the news coming out of Albany. We will keep you informed as we know. 


Update from NY State of Health:
Dear New York State Educators,
Please share this information with families in your community. As we work through these challenging times together, NY State of Health is committed to ensuring access to affordable, quality health insurance for all New Yorkers so they can get the care they need during this state of emergency.

With the recent closure of businesses across the state, many New Yorkers are at risk of losing their health insurance coverage as a result of COVID-19. Many are likely to be eligible for health
coverage with financial assistance through NY State of Health due to their loss of coverage and
income. NY State of Health opened a Special Enrollment Period last month for people who are
uninsured, and the Marketplace has started an awareness campaign to let people know that NY
State of Health is there as a safety net in difficult times like these.

New Yorkers who are without health insurance should apply now through NY State of Health. If
you lost employer coverage, you must apply within 60 days of losing that coverage. Because of a
loss of income, New Yorkers may also be eligible for Medicaid, the Essential Plan, Child Health
Plus, or subsidized Qualified Health Plan coverage.

Thousands of assistors are ready throughout the state to help consumers enroll by phone. NY
State of Health is committed to helping New Yorkers get the coverage they need so they can get
the care they need.

Visit us at: www.nystateofhealth.ny.gov and let us help you find a health care plan that works
for you. If you have additional questions you can contact the Marketplace directly at 518-486-9102 or NYSOH@health.ny.gov. 

April 2 Updates
Family survey (click here) about our online learning process: 
Please take a couple of minutes to fill out the survey linked above. This will help us to continuously improve our communication with students as we work through the school closing. 

Parents - Is your child engaged? If your child is not doing any classwork, that’s a problem. Our teachers are making things available. 
Students need to put some effort into this online/distance world we’re in right now. 
If there are problems with communication, please let me know. You can call the office at 607-869-9636. Extension 3101 gets you directly to my office. If I’m not there, it transfers to my cell phone after a few rings. 

A message from Mrs. Tina Hallock, our family navigator:
The Family Navigator program is a service of the Racker Center in Ithaca. 

Hello fellow mamas and papas,
As we all deal with Covid-19 virus effects, I wanted to touch base. Lots of the messages we are receiving from the world are about change in the way we operate with each other in very understandable, proactive, protective ways. What I wanted to assure you that the ways in which I support you will change very little. I realize that connection, in whatever creative way we can think of, is essential to maintain our mental health. I will try to check in on each of you I have regular contact with this week and please feel free to contact me in whatever way serves you. If you have never connected with me and want to, please call, text or email. If being with your family is what you need to do, please do so. If part of your self-care is touching base with me, please reach out. Remember that much of my purpose is to help you hold the hard stuff. I have others who help me hold my hard stuff and it amazes me how calming it feels. 

All of that said, our book club will NOT meet in person and we are currently looking into how we can virtually meet. Racker has a meeting this morning and exploring this very option. Please stay connected and please stay tuned. Take good care of yourselves, as you do what you do best, look out for your families.
Warmly,
Tina Hallock
Information about our Family Navigator program is located on our website at this link. 





March 31 Updates

Update video: Please check out our new Updates video. Chamberlain Bauder, Mr. Green and I have a new video out today. We’ll try to come out with a new video every few days. 

Free books (from Ms. Gale in the library): http://southseneca.libguides.com/library Students and teachers can access to order their 2 free books - DG Literacy $$ (it's currently running on Instagram @ssmh_library, forum slides and on the resource page which goes to the library page).

Students and staff can simply click the link in the top left corner of the Library page and fill out the form with the title and author and then I can order them...25 students and 3 teachers have already ordered in middle school, but I'd like it to reach the HS students and teachers too...I'd like to get an order in asap with 50 people at a time so it's not so overwhelming as it was last year :) I will keep it open until we get back to school, but if people order now, they may have them before they return.

March 25 Updates
Assignments during spring break: We’ve been modifying our schedule. If you get assignments during the week of April 6 to 10, you should work on them. 

Tech issues?
Please direct outside callers for CTS to call the Helpdesk at 4116 during the Pandemic closure,
This number will be staffed as possible, and throughout the school day. Voicemail messages left at this mailbox will notify all CTS staff.


March 23 Updates
From Brooke Habberfield, our social worker: 
Hi Everyone,
I’m aware this time can be rough for many people. I wanted to remind/share the crisis line info that anyone can use. Crisis Text Line is the free, 24/7, confidential text message service for people in crisis. Text HOME to 741741 in the United States. Or you can call the National Suicide Prevention Lifeline-The Lifeline provides 24/7, free and confidential support for people in distress, prevention and crisis resources for you or your loved ones, and best practices for professionals. Call 1-800-273-8255.

March 20 Updates
Tech help: Please note that our CTS department cannot help with access questions relating to cell phones. Students should be encouraged to use their Chromebooks. Maybe I’m old (yes I am), but a regular keyboard with a larger screen makes school work easier!

Need your stuff? Call the office and leave a voicemail. You can also call my extension at 3101. Calls to that extension are currently coming to my cell phone. 

Health office update, from Mrs. Ganoung:
We, your school nurses, are here to help you during this uncertain time. We will be taking calls each weekday from 8:00am until 3:30 pm beginning Monday, March 23, 2020. March 19 Updates
Quite a few people picked up materials today; thanks for that. If you need anything, please call the school at 869-9636. We will be limiting office hours going forward to increase social distancing, but we will always check voice mails and emails.

BOCES students (from Mr. Casler at BOCES): We will be continuing to provide supplemental learning activities to all our BOCES students throughout this most unique of times. Each teacher has contacted the students they serve. Many of our staff are continuing via Google classroom. Some of our staff has distributed more traditional materials as well. March 18 Updates
From Mrs. Bauder for MS students: Please check your shared with me folders on the drive daily for Forum Slides. I have already had the chance to let 7th graders know this while we were in session on Monday. Since it is already a routine access point for information for our MS students, I thought I would continue to do that. It may be a way to give students a bit of "normalcy" in this very unusual time. I plan to continue the mission of Forum daily, with regards to photos, a song, birthday celebrations, announcements, suggestions, focus on our monthly theme (March is Integrity). 

Today I included a suggestion about physical activity with some links to a calendar to chart themselves and another link to a yoga for beginners video. It is a way to keep some "middle school" in our process.
Thanks Mrs. Bauder!





Guidance Department Communication Links Class Resource Links For Closing

March 17 Updates

We’re writing to provide you with some important updates regarding our recently announced school closings. A two-week school closing is rather unprecedented in New York State. Despite this, we’ve taken this action to help prevent community transmission of the COVID-19 virus and protect the health of our students, staff, and community.
As a reminder: Our school will be closed until April 13 (returning the 14th). During this school closing, all co-curricular and extracurricular activities (including all athletics) are cancelled.
Here are a few important updates on what this closing means for your child/children and family:

1. Academics and Instruction: Our teachers have been working hard to prepare instructional resources for our students. Some of our teachers have sent home work already; others have been preparing resources that will be shared with students electronically. 
The folder linked here has all of our school closing files relating to the Middle/High School. 
The file linked here (and above) has classroom resources. More coming every day. 

2. Technology: Many of the resources we are sharing with students require technology (device and internet) to access. As for general technical support, you may contact our CTS department between the hours of 7:00 AM and 4:30 PM. The email is helpdesk@southseneca.org. If you need to speak with someone right away about a Chromebook issue, please call the school at 869-9636. They will respond as soon as possible. 

3. Food Services: 
Food service updates: Our food service team is making calls over the next 24 hours. We will be setting things up with families who could use the help. More to come. 

Ovid Food Pantry
Open every Monday from 8 a.m.-1 p.m. Bring bags/boxes

Ovid Food Truck
Every other Tuesday from 3 p.m.-5 p.m. Next date is March 17. Service will be a parking lot pick up effective March 17 until further notice

For other food emergencies: 
Call the Ovid Federated Church
9 a.m.-1 p.m. M-F 607-869-2794; after hours call Nancy Canniff 607-351-0720
 
4. School Offices: Currently, we plan to have our school offices open from 8:00 AM to 3:00 PM daily. This could change as the situation changes (as well as our individual health). We are asking parents and students to refrain from visiting our schools (or school grounds), except for when visiting to pick up meals or instructional resources in designated areas. We are taking these steps to maintain “social distancing” and protect the safety and welfare of our staff and visitors. 




5. Website: The school website will continue to serve as the best source for up to date district news. We will be posting our most up-to-date information for students, parents, and staff on this page. We’ve also included links to state and federal websites with accurate information on the coronavirus pandemic.

6. Child Care: an extended school closing can present families with a significant challenge when it comes to child care. The New York State Office of Children and Family Services maintains a website to assist families in accessing child care in our state. You can get more information at www.ocfs.ny.gov/programs/childcare.

7. Talking with Children About COVID-19: the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention has offered the following tips/guidelines for talking with children about the coronavirus pandemic:
a. Remain calm and reassuring- children react to what you say and how you say it.
b. Make yourself available to listen and talk with your children.
c. Avoid language that blames others---viruses can make anyone sick, regardless of race, ethnicity, or other factors.
d. Pay attention to what children see or hear in the media---too much information on any one topic can cause anxiety, particularly for children.
e. Provide children information and answers that are honest and accurate.
f. Teach children everyday actions that can reduce the spread of germs, including handwashing, avoiding people who are sick/ill, and properly covering/catching their coughs and sneezes.

8. Other Mental Health Concerns: We are working to have our School Counselors available on a call in basis. For middle and high school students, Mr. Green will be available through Remind App & Google Classroom. Please see Mr. Green’s communication page, also linked on the top. Brooke Habberfield will remain available to all K-12 students and parents alike for counseling or to discuss other concerns as needed via email. 

9. If You've Traveled: even with our schools now closed for two weeks, it's important for you to notify your child's school if you, your child, or another family member travel to high risk exposure areas (inside the USA) or travel outside the country.

These are challenging times for everyone---our students, their families, our faculty and staff, and our entire community. We commend our staff for their dedication and professionalism during this pandemic and we extend our thanks to you, our South Seneca families, for your understanding, your flexibility, and your support.
We will continue to email you with new information and updates and we encourage you to visit our website frequently for up-to-date information on our district’s response to this pandemic.

Tim Houseknecht "},{"ty":"is","ibi":20653,"s":"Middle/High School Spring 2020 School Closing Info
